I think this is a great Idea! But im kind of thorn with regards to the implementation. 

I do have another library (https://github.com/mpratt/RelativeTime) that calculates relative dates, with support for multiple languages. I could add it as a composer requirement and then work from there, but Im not sure if I want to add dependencies to this library.

On the other Hand, I think it would be better if each provider returns a `date_relative` key instead of specifying a configuration option, as in `$config = ['date_format' => '-'];`. 

That would be easier to implement, because it would be a matter of just adding a new key in the `translate` method

```php
    $result[$id] = array_merge($data, array(
        'link' => $link,
        'date_relative' => $this->relativeDate($data['stamp']),
        'date' => date($this->config['date_format'], (int) $data['stamp']),
        'html' => str_replace('{link}', $link, $language->get($data['type'])),
    ));
```

However, I'm not sure about how to implement the language translation. Perhaps the best bet would be to modify the `Language Adapter` to support multiple arguments (using sprintf) and have the (lets call it for now) `relativeDate` method return something like `array('quantity' => 5, 'unit' => '{minutes}')`.

So in Theory the `translate` method could be modified as:

```php
$relativeDate = $this->relativeDate($data['stamp']);
// returns array('quantity' => 5, 'unit' => '{minutes}');

 $result[$id] = array_merge($data, array(
       ....
       'date_relative' => $language->get($relativeDate['unit'], $relativeDate['quantity']),
       .....
  );
.....
```

And have a translation key  named (in this case) {minutes}, that maps to
```php
 // For English 
 protected $translation = array(
    {minutes} => '%s minutes ago',
);

// In spanish it would be
 protected $translation = array(
    {minutes} => 'hace %s minutos',
);
```
But Im not confident if that would be the best way to go. I like the Idea of having relative dates, but like I said, im not sure about the implementation. Using my other library it would be just as simple as instantiating the object, giving the language and call the `timeAgo` method. But who likes having dependecies? :(

This month is going to be a busy one for me, so Im not going to make any promises, I could try to implement it at the end of the month, but If you would like to tackle this feature, go ahead and send me a PR!!
